{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643220,"nonce":"9fRpBcKs+sd/qc12wmPprSGkQu4=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\nThe phrase \"trained-robust vs trained-baseline models\" is ambiguous. In the context of Part 2 analysis (SISU-conditioned networks), these terms refer to:\n\n- \"trained-robust\": Models trained with nonzero perturbation standard deviation (pert_std \u003e 0) under the PAI-ASF method. The specific architecture (GRU vs vRNN), gating mode (additive vs multiplicative), and training method (standard backprop vs minimax adversarial) are NOT specified here because this analysis module is designed to be run across multiple model configurations. The module parameterizes over \"training perturbation std\" as its comparison axis.\n\n- \"trained-baseline\": Models trained with pert_std=0 (no perturbation during training) but still receiving SISU input. These serve as a control for the effect of perturbation training on feedback gain modulation.\n\nThe module uses `lohi` to contrast the extreme training conditions (lowest vs highest pert_std in the loaded model set), so the exact models compared depend on which models are loaded at analysis time.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}